Yes — in the manager round, asking a few thoughtful questions about the team and project is very helpful. It shows interest, maturity, and ownership mindset. You don’t need many questions; 2–3 good ones are enough.

Here are some safe and impressive questions you can ask.

1️⃣ Ask About the Project

Could you share more about the current projects the team is working on and the main challenges you are trying to solve?

Why this works:

Shows curiosity

Shows you want to understand the business problem

2️⃣ Ask About Your Role in the Team

If I join the team, what would be the key responsibilities or priorities in the first few months?

Why this works:

Shows you are already thinking about contributing

Managers like candidates who think about impact early

3️⃣ Ask About Team Structure

How is the team currently structured, and how do engineers usually collaborate on features?

Why this works:

Shows interest in teamwork and collaboration

4️⃣ Ask About Success Criteria (Very Good Question)

What would success look like in this role after 6–12 months?

Why this is powerful:

Shows long-term thinking

Managers really like this question

5️⃣ Ask About Tech Growth (Optional)

Are there opportunities to work on architecture decisions or technical improvements within the team?

Good for 5+ year engineers because it signals senior thinking.

Important Tips

Ask only 2–3 questions, not too many.

Good combination:

Project challenges

First 3–6 month expectations

Success criteria

Example Ending

You could say:

Thanks for explaining the role. I had a couple of questions about the team and project if that’s okay.

Then ask your questions.

If you want, I can also tell you one question you should NEVER ask in the manager round (it can reduce your chances even if you performed well).